The PipelineTool ignores the attributes but DefaultValue (only this one, coincidence with String ?) if any are set. 
Instead of reading the attributes DisplayName and Description (if it was intended to be shown in ballons/tooltip ?) it only shows the property name:

```
[DisplayName("Normal Map Texture")]
[Description("blablabla")]
[DefaultValue("")]
public string MAP_Normal_Texture
{
    get { return normalMapTexture; }
    set { normalMapTexture = value; }
}
private string normalMapTexture;
```

Here it shows MAP_Normal_Texture, instead of Normal Map Texture.

When a custom processor exposes a string property in the pipeline tool, it crashes (it seems this happens only with nullable types, not only String):

```
public string MAP_Normal_Texture
{
    get { return normalMapTexture; }
    set { normalMapTexture = value; }
}
private string normalMapTexture;
```

If a user clicks on the textbox to edit the field of MAP_Normal_Texture, the pipeline tool crashes and no error message available.

But if normalMapTexture is initialized to "", then no crash happens and everything rolls.

XNA has a [BlendFactor](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/microsoft.xna.framework.graphics.graphicsdevice.blendfactor.aspx) property in GraphicsDevice that is currently missing in MonoGame. Note that there is also a [BlendFactor](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/microsoft.xna.framework.graphics.blendstate.blendfactor.aspx) property variable in BlendState. I wrote a quick test to see how it works in XNA:

```
[Test]
public void BlendFactor()
{
    Assert.AreEqual(Color.White, gd.BlendFactor);

    var blend = new BlendState
    {
        BlendFactor = Color.Crimson
    };

    gd.BlendState = blend;
    Assert.AreEqual(Color.Crimson, gd.BlendFactor);

    gd.BlendFactor = Color.CornflowerBlue;
    Assert.AreEqual(Color.Crimson, gd.BlendState.BlendFactor);
    Assert.AreEqual(Color.CornflowerBlue, gd.BlendFactor);

    blend.Dispose();
}
```

This passes, so to get the same behavior in MG we just need to add a `public Color BlendFactor { get; set; }` and then in the BlendState setter set `BlendFactor = value.BlendFactor`. I don't know if this property should just override the BlendFactor from the BlendState, but my guess is that's how it works. XNA docs are ambiguous on this and just say both control blend factor...

When compiling shaders it is common to have warnings such as 

' warning X3206: 'mul': implicit truncation of vector type;

at the moment, if we get these warnings the pipeline tool flags those as 'failed'.

There is a bug in the current dev build that makes the Pipeline tool hang and crash. It can be reproduced like this:

-Add multiple assets to the `Content`, for example `SpriteFont`s;
-Make all of them have a different value for `TextureFormat` (that's where I found the bug but it likely affects the other properties as well);
-Use `Multiselect` on the `SpriteFont`s and try to change `TextureFormat`'s value for all of them.

Tested on Win10 Pro. x64.
